# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: knot-theory
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] In mathematics, the **Alexander polynomial** is a knot invariant which assigns a polynomial with integer coefficients to each knot type.
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] James Waddell Alexander II discovered this, the first knot polynomial, in 1923.
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] In 1969, John Conway showed a version of this polynomial, now called the **Alexander–Conway polynomial**, could be computed using a skein relation, although its significance was not realized until the discovery of the Jones polynomial in 1984.
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] Soon after Conway's reworking of the Alexander polynomial, it was realized that a similar skein relation was exhibited in Alexander's paper on his polynomial.
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] Let *X* be the infinite cyclic cover of the knot complement of *K*.
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] This covering can be obtained by cutting the knot complement along a Seifert surface of *K* and gluing together infinitely many copies of the resulting manifold with boundary in a cyclic manner.
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] There is a covering transformation *t* acting on *X*.
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] Consider the first homology (with integer coefficients) of *X*, denoted $H_{1}(X)$ .
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] The transformation *t* acts on the homology and so we can consider $H_{1}(X)$ a module over the ring of Laurent polynomials $\mathbb {Z} [t,t^{-1}]$ .
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] This is called the **Alexander invariant** or **Alexander module**.
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] The module is finitely presentable; a presentation matrix for this module is called the **Alexander matrix**.
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] If the number of generators, r , is less than or equal to the number of relations, s , then we consider the ideal generated by all $r\times r$ minors of the matrix; this is the zeroth Fitting ideal or **Alexander ideal** and does not depend on choice of presentation matrix.
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] If the Alexander ideal is principal, take a generator; this is called an Alexander polynomial of the knot.
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] Since this is only unique up to multiplication by the Laurent monomial $\pm t^{n}$ , one often fixes a particular unique form.
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] Alexander's choice of normalization is to make the polynomial have a positive constant term.
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] Alexander proved that the Alexander ideal is nonzero and always principal.
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] Thus an Alexander polynomial always exists, and is clearly a knot invariant, denoted $\Delta _{K}(t)$ .
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] It turns out that the Alexander polynomial of a knot is the same polynomial for the mirror image knot.
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] In other words, it cannot distinguish between a knot and its mirror image.
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] The following procedure for computing the Alexander polynomial was given by J.
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] Take an oriented diagram of the knot with n crossings; there are $n+2$ regions of the knot diagram.
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] To work out the Alexander polynomial, first one must create an incidence matrix of size $(n,n+2)$ .
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] The n rows correspond to the n crossings, and the $n+2$ columns to the regions.
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] The values for the matrix entries are either $0,1,-1,t,-t$ .
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] Consider the entry corresponding to a particular region and crossing.
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] If the region is not adjacent to the crossing, the entry is 0.
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] If the region is adjacent to the crossing, the entry depends on its location.
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] The following table gives the entry, determined by the location of the region at the crossing from the perspective of the incoming undercrossing line.
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] Remove two columns corresponding to adjacent regions from the matrix, and work out the determinant of the new $n\times n$ matrix.
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] Depending on the columns removed, the answer will differ by multiplication by $\pm t^{n}$ , where the power of n is not necessarily the number of crossings in the knot.
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] To resolve this ambiguity, divide out the largest possible power of t and multiply by $-1$ if necessary, so that the constant term is positive.
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] For example, this shows immediately that the Alexander polynomial of the unknot is 1 (though this follows also immediately from the definition).
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] The Alexander polynomial can also be computed from the Seifert matrix.
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] Alexander, Ralph Fox considered a copresentation of the knot group $\pi _{1}(S^{3}\backslash K)$ , and introduced non-commutative differential calculus, which also permits one to compute $\Delta _{K}(t)$ .
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] The Alexander polynomial is symmetric: $\Delta _{K}(t^{-1})=\Delta _{K}(t)$ for all knots K.
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] Furthermore, the Alexander polynomial evaluates to a unit on 1: $\Delta _{K}(1)=\pm 1$ .
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] defined as the order ideal of its infinite-cyclic covering space.
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] The value of the Alexander polynomial evaluated at -1 is known as the determinant of the knot.
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] Every integral Laurent polynomial which is both symmetric and evaluates to a unit at 1 is the Alexander polynomial of a knot.
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] Since the Alexander ideal is principal, $\Delta _{K}(t)=1$ if and only if the commutator subgroup of the knot group is perfect (i.e. equal to its own commutator subgroup).
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] For a topologically slice knot, the Alexander polynomial satisfies the Fox–Milnor condition $\Delta _{K}(t)=f(t)f(t^{-1})$ where $f(t)$ is some other integral Laurent polynomial.
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] Twice the knot genus is bounded below by the degree of the Alexander polynomial.
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] Michael Freedman proved that a knot in the 3-sphere is topologically slice; i.e., bounds a "locally-flat" topological disc in the 4-ball, if the Alexander polynomial of the knot is trivial.
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] Kauffman describes the first construction of the Alexander polynomial via state sums derived from physical models.
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] A survey of these topics and other connections with physics are given in.
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] There are other relations with surfaces and smooth 4-dimensional topology.
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] For example, under certain assumptions, there is a way of modifying a smooth 4-manifold by performing a surgery that consists of removing a neighborhood of a two-dimensional torus and replacing it with a knot complement crossed with *S*1.
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] The result is a smooth 4-manifold homeomorphic to the original, though now the Seiberg–Witten invariant has been modified by multiplication with the Alexander polynomial of the knot.
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] Knots with symmetries are known to have restricted Alexander polynomials.
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] Nonetheless, the Alexander polynomial can fail to detect some symmetries, such as strong invertibility.
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] If the knot complement fibers over the circle, then the Alexander polynomial of the knot is known to be *monic* (the coefficients of the highest and lowest order terms are equal to $\pm 1$ ).
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] In fact, if $S\to C_{K}\to S^{1}$ is a fiber bundle where $C_{K}$ is the knot complement, let $g:S\to S$ represent the monodromy, then $\Delta _{K}(t)={\rm {Det}}(tI-g_{*})$ where $g_{*}\colon H_{1}S\to H_{1}S$ is the induced map on homology.
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] If K is an untwisted Whitehead double, then $\Delta _{K}(t)=\pm 1$ .
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] The Alexander polynomial is not a complete invariant for knots, that is two distinct knots may have the same Alexander polynomial.
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] For example, according to the database KnotInfo there occurs only 212 unique Alexander polynomials among the 250 knots with up to 10 crossings.
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] The Alexander polynomial does not detect the unknot: there are infinitely many knots which have Alexander polynomial equal to 1.
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] For example, these include every Whitehead double of an untwisted knot.
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] Explicit examples of knots with few crossings having Alexander polynomial 1 are the Conway knot and the Kinoshita–Terasaka knot, both with 11 crossings.
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] In contrast, it is still unknown whether the Jones polynomial (or the stronger HOMFLY polynomial) determines the unknot.
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] The Alexander polynomial does not detect primeness of a knot, that is, a prime knot may have the same Alexander polynomial as a composite knot.
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] There are many more properties which are not detected by the Alexander polynomial.
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] Alexander proved the Alexander polynomial satisfies a skein relation.
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] John Conway later rediscovered this in a different form and showed that the skein relation together with a choice of value on the unknot was enough to determine the polynomial.
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] Conway's version is a polynomial in *z* with integer coefficients, denoted $\nabla (z)$ and called the **Alexander–Conway polynomial** (also known as **Conway polynomial** or **Conway–Alexander polynomial**).
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] Suppose we are given an oriented link diagram, where $L_{+},L_{-},L_{0}$ are link diagrams resulting from crossing and smoothing changes on a local region of a specified crossing of the diagram, as indicated in the figure.
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] The relationship to the standard Alexander polynomial is given by $\Delta _{L}(t^{2})=\nabla _{L}(t-t^{-1})$ .
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] Note that this relation gives a Laurent polynomial in *t1/2*.
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] See knot theory for an example computing the Conway polynomial of the trefoil.
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] Using pseudo-holomorphic curves, Ozsváth-Szabó and Rasmussen associated a bigraded abelian group, called knot Floer homology, to each isotopy class of knots.
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] The graded Euler characteristic of knot Floer homology is the Alexander polynomial.
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] While the Alexander polynomial gives a lower bound on the genus of a knot, Ozsváth-Szabó showed that knot Floer homology detects the genus.
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] Similarly, while the Alexander polynomial gives an obstruction to a knot complement fibering over the circle, Ni showed that knot Floer homology completely determines when a knot complement fibers over the circle.
[src:knot-theory/alexander-polynomial] The knot Floer homology groups are part of the Heegaard Floer homology family of invariants; see Floer homology for further discussion.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] In mathematics, the **braid group on *n* strands** (denoted $B_{n}$ ), also known as the **Artin braid group**, is the group whose elements are equivalence classes of n-braids (e.g. under ambient isotopy), and whose group operation is composition of braids (see § Introduction).
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] In this introduction let *n* = 4; the generalization to other values of *n* will be straightforward.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] Consider two sets of four items lying on a table, with the items in each set being arranged in a vertical line, and such that one set sits next to the other.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] (In the illustrations below, these are the black dots.) Using four strands, each item of the first set is connected with an item of the second set so that a one-to-one correspondence results.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] The composition of the braids σ and τ is written as στ.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] The set of all braids on four strands is denoted by $B_{4}$ .
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] The above composition of braids is indeed a group operation.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] The identity element is the braid consisting of four parallel horizontal strands, and the inverse of a braid consists of that braid which "undoes" whatever the first braid did, which is obtained by flipping a diagram such as the ones above across a vertical line going through its centre.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] Braid theory has recently been applied to fluid mechanics, specifically to the field of chaotic mixing in fluid flows.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] Another field of intense investigation involving braid groups and related topological concepts in the context of quantum physics is in the theory and (conjectured) experimental implementation of the proposed particles anyons.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] These have been proposed as the basis for error-corrected quantum computing and so their abstract study is currently of fundamental importance in quantum information.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] To put the above informal discussion of braid groups on firm ground, one needs to use the homotopy concept of algebraic topology, defining braid groups as fundamental groups of a configuration space.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] Alternatively, one can define the braid group purely algebraically via the braid relations, keeping the pictures in mind only to guide the intuition.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] To explain how to reduce a braid group in the sense of Artin to a fundamental group, we consider a connected manifold X of dimension at least 2.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] The *symmetric product* of n copies of X means the quotient of $X^{n}$ (the n -fold Cartesian product of X ) by the permutation action of the symmetric group on n strands operating on the indices of coordinates.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] That is, an ordered n -tuple is in the same orbit as any other that is a re-ordered version of it.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] A path in the n -fold symmetric product is the abstract way of discussing n points of X , considered as an unordered n -tuple, independently tracing out n strings.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] Since we must require that the strings never pass through each other, it is necessary that we pass to the subspace Y of the symmetric product, of orbits of n -tuples of *distinct* points.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] That is, we remove all the subspaces of $X^{n}$ defined by conditions $x_{i}=x_{j}$ for all $1\leq i<j\leq n$ .
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] This is invariant under the symmetric group, and Y is the quotient by the symmetric group of the non-excluded n -tuples.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] Under the dimension condition Y will be connected.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] With this definition, then, we can call **the braid group of X with n strings** the fundamental group of Y (for any choice of base point – this is well-defined up to isomorphism).
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] The case where X is the Euclidean plane is the original one of Artin.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] In some cases it can be shown that the higher homotopy groups of Y are trivial.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] When *X* is the plane, the braid can be *closed*, i.e., corresponding ends can be connected in pairs, to form a link, i.e., a possibly intertwined union of possibly knotted loops in three dimensions.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] The number of components of the link can be anything from 1 to *n*, depending on the permutation of strands determined by the link.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] Alexander demonstrates that every link can be obtained in this way as the "closure" of a braid.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] Different braids can give rise to the same link, just as different crossing diagrams can give rise to the same knot.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] In 1935, Andrey Markov Jr. described two moves on braid diagrams that yield equivalence in the corresponding closed braids.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] A single-move version of Markov's theorem, was published in 1997.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] Vaughan Jones originally defined his polynomial as a braid invariant and then showed that it depended only on the class of the closed braid.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] The Markov theorem gives necessary and sufficient conditions under which the closures of two braids are equivalent links.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] The "braid index" is the least number of strings needed to make a closed braid representation of a link.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] It is equal to the least number of Seifert circles in any projection of a knot.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] Braid groups were introduced explicitly by Emil Artin in 1925, although (as Wilhelm Magnus pointed out in 1974) they were already implicit in Adolf Hurwitz's work on monodromy from 1891.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] Braid groups may be described by explicit presentations, as was shown by Artin in 1947.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] Braid groups are also understood by a deeper mathematical interpretation: as the fundamental group of certain configuration spaces.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] As Magnus says, Hurwitz gave the interpretation of a braid group as the fundamental group of a configuration space (cf. braid theory), an interpretation that was lost from view until it was rediscovered by Ralph Fox and Lee Neuwirth in 1962.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] Joan Birman’s book *Braids, Links, and Mapping Class Groups* (1974) was the first book devoted to braid groups.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] Every braid in $B_{4}$ can be written as a composition of a number of these braids and their inverses.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] In other words, these three braids generate the group $B_{4}$ .
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] To see this, an arbitrary braid is scanned from left to right for crossings.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] Numbering the strands beginning at the top, whenever a crossing of strands i and $i+1$ is encountered, $\sigma _{i}$ or $\sigma _{i}^{-1}$ is written down, depending on whether strand i moves over or under strand $i+1$ .
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] Upon reaching the right end, the braid has been written as a product of the $\sigma _{i}$ and their inverses.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] (these relations can be appreciated best by drawing the braid on a piece of paper).
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] It can be shown that all other relations among the braids $\sigma _{1}$ , $\sigma _{2}$ and $\sigma _{3}$ already follow from these relations and the group axioms.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] where in the first group of relations $1\leq i\leq n-2$ and in the second group of relations $|i-j|\geq 2$ .
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] This presentation leads to generalisations of braid groups called Artin groups.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] The cubic relations, known as the **braid relations**, play an important role in the theory of Yang–Baxter equations.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] By forgetting how the strands twist and cross, every braid on *n* strands determines a permutation on *n* elements.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] This assignment is onto and compatible with composition, and therefore becomes a surjective group homomorphism *Bn* → *Sn* from the braid group onto the symmetric group.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] The image of the braid σ*i* ∈ *Bn* is the transposition *s**i* = (*i*, *i*+1) ∈ *Sn*.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] These transpositions generate the symmetric group, satisfy the braid group relations, and have order 2.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] The kernel of the homomorphism *Bn* → *Sn* is the subgroup of *Bn* called the **pure braid group on *n* strands** and denoted *Pn*.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] This can be seen as the fundamental group of the space of *n*-tuples of distinct points of the Euclidean plane.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] In a pure braid, the beginning and the end of each strand are in the same position.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] This sequence splits and therefore pure braid groups are realized as iterated semi-direct products of free groups.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] Furthermore, the modular group has trivial center, and thus the modular group is isomorphic to the quotient group of $B_{3}$ modulo its center, $Z(B_{3}),$ and equivalently, to the group of inner automorphisms of $B_{3}$ .
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] Here is a construction of this isomorphism.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] From the braid relations it follows that $a^{2}=b^{3}$ .
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] implying that c is in the center of $B_{3}$ .
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] Let C denote the subgroup of $B_{3}$ generated by *c*, since *C* ⊂ *Z*(*B*3), it is a normal subgroup and one may take the quotient group *B*3/*C*.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] We claim *B*3/*C* ≅ PSL(2, **Z**); this isomorphism can be given an explicit form.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] where *L* and *R* are the standard left and right moves on the Stern–Brocot tree; it is well known that these moves generate the modular group.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] Mapping *a* to *v* and *b* to *p* yields a surjective group homomorphism *B*3 → PSL(2, **Z**).
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] The center of *B*3 is equal to *C*, a consequence of the facts that *c* is in the center, the modular group has trivial center, and the above surjective homomorphism has kernel *C*.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] The braid group *Bn* can be shown to be isomorphic to the mapping class group of a punctured disk with *n* punctures.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] This is most easily visualized by imagining each puncture as being connected by a string to the boundary of the disk; each mapping homomorphism that permutes two of the punctures can then be seen to be a homotopy of the strings, that is, a braiding of these strings.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] Via this mapping class group interpretation of braids, each braid may be classified as periodic, reducible or pseudo-Anosov.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] If a braid is given and one connects the first left-hand item to the first right-hand item using a new string, the second left-hand item to the second right-hand item etc.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] (without creating any braids in the new strings), one obtains a link, and sometimes a knot.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] Alexander's theorem in braid theory states that the converse is true as well: every knot and every link arises in this fashion from at least one braid; such a braid can be obtained by cutting the link.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] Since braids can be concretely given as words in the generators σ*i*, this is often the preferred method of entering knots into computer programs.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] The word problem for the braid relations is efficiently solvable and there exists a normal form for elements of *Bn* in terms of the generators σ1, ..., σ*n*−1.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] (In essence, computing the normal form of a braid is the algebraic analogue of "pulling the strands" as illustrated in our second set of images above.) The free GAP computer algebra system can carry out computations in *Bn* if the elements are given in terms of these generators.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] There is also a package called *CHEVIE* for GAP3 with special support for braid groups.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] The word problem is also efficiently solved via the Lawrence–Krammer representation.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] In addition to the word problem, there are several known hard computational problems that could implement braid groups, applications in cryptography have been suggested.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] In analogy with the action of the symmetric group by permutations, in various mathematical settings there exists a natural action of the braid group on *n*-tuples of objects or on the *n*-folded tensor product that involves some "twists".
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] Consider an arbitrary group *G* and let *X* be the set of all *n*-tuples of elements of *G* whose product is the identity element of *G*.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] Thus the elements *xi* and *x**i*+1 exchange places and, in addition, *xi* is twisted by the inner automorphism corresponding to *x**i*+1 – this ensures that the product of the components of *x* remains the identity element.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] It may be checked that the braid group relations are satisfied and this formula indeed defines a group action of *Bn* on *X*.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] As another example, a braided monoidal category is a monoidal category with a braid group action.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] Such structures play an important role in modern mathematical physics and lead to quantum knot invariants.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] Elements of the braid group *Bn* can be represented more concretely by matrices.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] One classical such representation is Burau representation, where the matrix entries are single variable Laurent polynomials.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] It had been a long-standing question whether Burau representation was faithful, but the answer turned out to be negative for *n* ≥ 5.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] More generally, it was a major open problem whether braid groups were linear.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] In 1990, Ruth Lawrence described a family of more general "Lawrence representations" depending on several parameters.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] In 1996, Chetan Nayak and Frank Wilczek posited that in analogy to projective representations of SO(3), the projective representations of the braid group have a physical meaning for certain quasiparticles in the fractional quantum hall effect.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] Around 2001 Stephen Bigelow and Daan Krammer independently proved that all braid groups are linear.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] Their work used the Lawrence–Krammer representation of dimension $n(n-1)/2$ depending on the variables *q* and *t*.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] By suitably specializing these variables, the braid group $B_{n}$ may be realized as a subgroup of the general linear group over the complex numbers.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] There are many ways to generalize this notion to an infinite number of strands.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] The simplest way is to take the direct limit of braid groups, where the attaching maps $f\colon B_{n}\to B_{n+1}$ send the $n-1$ generators of $B_{n}$ to the first $n-1$ generators of $B_{n+1}$ (i.e., by attaching a trivial strand).
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] This group, however, admits no metrizable topology while remaining continuous.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] Paul Fabel has shown that there are two topologies that can be imposed on the resulting group each of whose completion yields a different group.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] The first is a very tame group and is isomorphic to the mapping class group of the infinitely punctured disk—a discrete set of punctures limiting to the boundary of the disk.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] The second group can be thought of the same as with finite braid groups.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] Place a strand at each of the points $(0,1/n)$ and the set of all braids—where a braid is defined to be a collection of paths from the points $(0,1/n,0)$ to the points $(0,1/n,1)$ so that the function yields a permutation on endpoints—is isomorphic to this wilder group.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] The cohomology of a group G is defined as the cohomology of the corresponding Eilenberg–MacLane classifying space, $K(G,1)$ , which is a CW complex uniquely determined by G up to homotopy.
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] The calculations for coefficients in $\mathbb {Z} /2\mathbb {Z}$ can be found in Fuks (1970).
[src:knot-theory/braid-group] Similarly, a classifying space for the pure braid group $P_{n}$ is $\operatorname {Conf} _{n}(\mathbb {R} ^{2})$ , the *n*th *ordered* configuration space of $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ .
[src:knot-theory/jones-polynomial] In the mathematical field of knot theory, the **Jones polynomial** is a knot polynomial discovered by Vaughan Jones in 1984.
[src:knot-theory/jones-polynomial] Specifically, it is an invariant of an oriented knot or link which assigns to each oriented knot or link a Laurent polynomial in the variable $t^{1/2}$ with integer coefficients.
[src:knot-theory/jones-polynomial] Suppose we have an oriented link L , given as a knot diagram.
[src:knot-theory/jones-polynomial] We will define the Jones polynomial $V(L)$ by using Louis Kauffman's bracket polynomial, which we denote by $\langle ~\rangle$ .
[src:knot-theory/jones-polynomial] Here the bracket polynomial is a Laurent polynomial in the variable A with integer coefficients.
[src:knot-theory/jones-polynomial] where $w(L)$ denotes the writhe of L in its given diagram.
[src:knot-theory/jones-polynomial] The writhe of a diagram is the number of positive crossings ( $L_{+}$ in the figure below) minus the number of negative crossings ( $L_{-}$ ).
[src:knot-theory/jones-polynomial] $X(L)$ is a knot invariant since it is invariant under changes of the diagram of L by the three Reidemeister moves.
[src:knot-theory/jones-polynomial] Invariance under type II and III Reidemeister moves follows from invariance of the bracket under those moves.
[src:knot-theory/jones-polynomial] The bracket polynomial is known to change by a factor of $-A^{\pm 3}$ under a type I Reidemeister move.
[src:knot-theory/jones-polynomial] The definition of the X polynomial given above is designed to nullify this change, since the writhe changes appropriately by $+1$ or $-1$ under type I moves.
[src:knot-theory/jones-polynomial] Now make the substitution $A=t^{-1/4}$ in $X(L)$ to get the Jones polynomial $V(L)$ .
[src:knot-theory/jones-polynomial] This results in a Laurent polynomial with integer coefficients in the variable $t^{1/2}$ .
[src:knot-theory/jones-polynomial] This construction of the Jones polynomial for tangles is a simple generalization of the Kauffman bracket of a link.
[src:knot-theory/jones-polynomial] The construction was developed by Vladimir Turaev and published in 1990.
[src:knot-theory/jones-polynomial] Let k be a non-negative integer and $S_{k}$ denote the set of all isotopic types of tangle diagrams, with $2k$ ends, having no crossing points and no closed components (smoothings).
[src:knot-theory/jones-polynomial] Jones' original formulation of his polynomial came from his study of operator algebras.
[src:knot-theory/jones-polynomial] In Jones' approach, it resulted from a kind of "trace" of a particular braid representation into an algebra which originally arose while studying certain models, e.g. the Potts model, in statistical mechanics.
[src:knot-theory/jones-polynomial] A theorem of Alexander states that it is the trace closure of a braid, say with *n* strands.
[src:knot-theory/jones-polynomial] Now define a representation $\rho$ of the braid group on *n* strands, *Bn*, into the Temperley–Lieb algebra $\operatorname {TL} _{n}$ with coefficients in $\mathbb {Z} [A,A^{-1}]$ and $\delta =-A^{2}-A^{-2}$ .
[src:knot-theory/jones-polynomial] The standard braid generator $\sigma _{i}$ is sent to $A\cdot e_{i}+A^{-1}\cdot 1$ , where $1,e_{1},\dots ,e_{n-1}$ are the standard generators of the Temperley–Lieb algebra.
[src:knot-theory/jones-polynomial] It can be checked easily that this defines a representation.
[src:knot-theory/jones-polynomial] Take the braid word $\sigma$ obtained previously from L and compute $\delta ^{n-1}\operatorname {tr} \rho (\sigma )$ where $\operatorname {tr}$ is the Markov trace.
[src:knot-theory/jones-polynomial] This gives $\langle L\rangle$ , where $\langle$ $\rangle$ is the bracket polynomial.
[src:knot-theory/jones-polynomial] This can be seen by considering, as Louis Kauffman did, the Temperley–Lieb algebra as a particular diagram algebra.
[src:knot-theory/jones-polynomial] An advantage of this approach is that one can pick similar representations into other algebras, such as the *R*-matrix representations, leading to "generalized Jones invariants".
[src:knot-theory/jones-polynomial] The definition of the Jones polynomial by the bracket makes it simple to show that for a knot K , the Jones polynomial of its mirror image is given by substitution of $t^{-1}$ for t in $V(K)$ .
[src:knot-theory/jones-polynomial] Thus, an amphicheiral knot, a knot equivalent to its mirror image, has palindromic entries in its Jones polynomial.
[src:knot-theory/jones-polynomial] See the article on skein relation for an example of a computation using these relations.
[src:knot-theory/jones-polynomial] Another remarkable property of this invariant states that the Jones polynomial of an alternating link is an alternating polynomial.
[src:knot-theory/jones-polynomial] This property was proved by Morwen Thistlethwaite in 1987.
[src:knot-theory/jones-polynomial] Another proof of this last property is due to Hernando Burgos-Soto, who also gave an extension of the property to tangles.
[src:knot-theory/jones-polynomial] The Jones polynomial is not a complete invariant.
[src:knot-theory/jones-polynomial] There exist an infinite number of non-equivalent knots that have the same Jones polynomial.
[src:knot-theory/jones-polynomial] An example of two distinct knots having the same Jones polynomial can be found in the book by Murasugi.
[src:knot-theory/jones-polynomial] For a positive integer N , the N -colored Jones polynomial $V_{N}(L,t)$ is a generalisation of the Jones polynomial.
[src:knot-theory/jones-polynomial] It is the Reshetikhin–Turaev invariant associated with the $(N+1)$ -irreducible representation of the quantum group $U_{q}({\mathfrak {sl}}_{2})$ .
[src:knot-theory/jones-polynomial] In this scheme, the Jones polynomial is the 1-colored Jones polynomial, the Reshetikhin-Turaev invariant associated to the standard representation (irreducible and two-dimensional) of $U_{q}({\mathfrak {sl}}_{2})$ .
[src:knot-theory/jones-polynomial] One thinks of the strands of a link as being "colored" by a representation, hence the name.
[src:knot-theory/jones-polynomial] These properties are deduced from the fact that colored Jones polynomials are Reshetikhin-Turaev invariants.
[src:knot-theory/jones-polynomial] Recall that by viewing a diagram of K as an element of the Temperley-Lieb algebra thanks to the Kauffman bracket, one recovers the Jones polynomial of K .
[src:knot-theory/jones-polynomial] The resulting element of $\mathbb {Q} (t)$ is the N -colored Jones polynomial.
[src:knot-theory/jones-polynomial] By substituting $e^{h}$ for the variable t of the Jones polynomial and expanding it as the series of h each of the coefficients turn to be the Vassiliev invariant of the knot K .
[src:knot-theory/jones-polynomial] In order to unify the Vassiliev invariants (or, finite type invariants), Maxim Kontsevich constructed the Kontsevich integral.
[src:knot-theory/jones-polynomial] The value of the Kontsevich integral, which is the infinite sum of 1, 3-valued chord diagrams, named the Jacobi chord diagrams, reproduces the Jones polynomial along with the ${\mathfrak {sl}}_{2}$ weight system studied by Dror Bar-Natan.
[src:knot-theory/jones-polynomial] In 2000 Mikhail Khovanov constructed a certain chain complex for knots and links and showed that the homology induced from it is a knot invariant (see Khovanov homology).
[src:knot-theory/jones-polynomial] The Jones polynomial is described as the Euler characteristic for this homology.
[src:knot-theory/jones-polynomial] It is an open question whether there is a nontrivial knot with Jones polynomial equal to that of the unknot.
[src:knot-theory/jones-polynomial] It is known that there are nontrivial *links* with Jones polynomial equal to that of the corresponding unlinks by the work of Morwen Thistlethwaite.
[src:knot-theory/jones-polynomial] The simplest such example has 15 essential crossings and consists of a trefoil knot linked to a figure-eight knot.
[src:knot-theory/jones-polynomial] Every prime knot with up to 24 crossings, of which there are over three hundred million, is known to have a non-trivial Jones polynomial.
[src:knot-theory/jones-polynomial] This was determined by computing the Jones polynomial of several trillion knot diagrams, and verifying those diagrams with trivial Jones polynomials corresponded to trivial knots.
[src:knot-theory/jones-polynomial] It was shown by Kronheimer and Mrowka that there is no nontrivial knot with Khovanov homology equal to that of the unknot.
[src:knot-theory/jones-polynomial] While no nontrivial knot is known to have the same Jones polynomial as the unknot, two or more knots may have the same Jones polynomial and require other invariants to distinguish them.
[src:knot-theory/jones-polynomial] Examples include the Conway knot and the Kinoshita-Terasaka knot, with 11 crossings.
[src:knot-theory/knot-group] In mathematics, a knot is an embedding of a circle into 3-dimensional Euclidean space.
[src:knot-theory/knot-group] Other conventions consider knots to be embedded in the 3-sphere, in which case the knot group is the fundamental group of its complement in $S^{3}$ .
[src:knot-theory/knot-group] Two equivalent knots have isomorphic knot groups, so the knot group is a knot invariant and can be used to distinguish between certain pairs of inequivalent knots.
[src:knot-theory/knot-group] This is because an equivalence between two knots is a self-homeomorphism of $\mathbb {R} ^{3}$ that is isotopic to the identity and sends the first knot onto the second.
[src:knot-theory/knot-group] Such a homeomorphism restricts onto a homeomorphism of the complements of the knots, and this restricted homeomorphism induces an isomorphism of fundamental groups.
[src:knot-theory/knot-group] However, it is possible for two inequivalent knots to have isomorphic knot groups (see below for an example).
[src:knot-theory/knot-group] The abelianization of a knot group is always isomorphic to the infinite cyclic group **Z**; this follows because the abelianization agrees with the first homology group, which can be easily computed.
[src:knot-theory/knot-group] The knot group (or fundamental group of an oriented link in general) can be computed in the Wirtinger presentation by a relatively simple algorithm.
[src:knot-theory/knot-invariant] In the mathematical field of knot theory, a **knot invariant** is a quantity (in a broad sense) defined for each knot which is the same for equivalent knots.
[src:knot-theory/knot-invariant] The equivalence is often given by ambient isotopy but can be given by homeomorphism.
[src:knot-theory/knot-invariant] Research on invariants is not only motivated by the basic problem of distinguishing one knot from another but also to understand fundamental properties of knots and their relations to other branches of mathematics.
[src:knot-theory/knot-invariant] Knot invariants are thus used in knot classification, both in "enumeration" and "duplication removal".
[src:knot-theory/knot-invariant] From the modern perspective, it is natural to define a knot invariant from a knot diagram.
[src:knot-theory/knot-invariant] Of course, it must be unchanged (that is to say, invariant) under the Reidemeister moves ("triangular moves").
[src:knot-theory/knot-invariant] Tricolorability (and *n*-colorability) is a particularly simple and common example.
[src:knot-theory/knot-invariant] Other examples are knot polynomials, such as the Jones polynomial, which are currently among the most useful invariants for distinguishing knots from one another, though currently it is not known whether there exists a knot polynomial which distinguishes all knots from each other.
[src:knot-theory/knot-invariant] However, there are invariants which distinguish the unknot from all other knots, such as Khovanov homology and knot Floer homology.
[src:knot-theory/knot-invariant] Other invariants can be defined by considering some integer-valued function of knot diagrams and taking its minimum value over all possible diagrams of a given knot.
[src:knot-theory/knot-invariant] This category includes the crossing number, which is the minimum number of crossings for any diagram of the knot, and the bridge number, which is the minimum number of bridges for any diagram of the knot.
[src:knot-theory/knot-invariant] Historically, many of the early knot invariants are not defined by first selecting a diagram but defined intrinsically, which can make computing some of these invariants a challenge.
[src:knot-theory/knot-invariant] For example, knot genus is particularly tricky to compute, but can be effective (for instance, in distinguishing mutants).
[src:knot-theory/knot-invariant] The complement of a knot itself (as a topological space) is known to be a "complete invariant" of the knot by the Gordon–Luecke theorem in the sense that it distinguishes the given knot from all other knots up to ambient isotopy and mirror image.
[src:knot-theory/knot-invariant] Some invariants associated with the knot complement include the knot group which is just the fundamental group of the complement.
[src:knot-theory/knot-invariant] The knot quandle is also a complete invariant in this sense but it is difficult to determine if two quandles are isomorphic.
[src:knot-theory/knot-invariant] The peripheral subgroup can also work as a complete invariant.
[src:knot-theory/knot-invariant] By Mostow–Prasad rigidity, the hyperbolic structure on the complement of a hyperbolic link is unique, which means the hyperbolic volume is an invariant for these knots and links.
[src:knot-theory/knot-invariant] Volume, and other hyperbolic invariants, have proven very effective, utilized in some of the extensive efforts at knot tabulation.
[src:knot-theory/knot-invariant] In recent years, there has been much interest in homological invariants of knots which categorify well-known invariants.
[src:knot-theory/knot-invariant] Heegaard Floer homology is a homology theory whose Euler characteristic is the Alexander polynomial of the knot.
[src:knot-theory/knot-invariant] It has been proven effective in deducing new results about the classical invariants.
[src:knot-theory/knot-invariant] Along a different line of study, there is a combinatorially defined cohomology theory of knots called Khovanov homology whose Euler characteristic is the Jones polynomial.
[src:knot-theory/knot-invariant] This has recently been shown to be useful in obtaining bounds on slice genus whose earlier proofs required gauge theory.
[src:knot-theory/knot-invariant] Mikhail Khovanov and Lev Rozansky have since defined several other related cohomology theories whose Euler characteristics recover other classical invariants.
[src:knot-theory/knot-invariant] Catharina Stroppel gave a representation theoretic interpretation of Khovanov homology by categorifying quantum group invariants.
[src:knot-theory/knot-invariant] There is also growing interest from both knot theorists and scientists in understanding "physical" or geometric properties of knots and relating it to topological invariants and knot type.
[src:knot-theory/knot-invariant] where *κ*(*p*) is the curvature at *p*, then *K* is an unknot.
[src:knot-theory/knot-invariant] An example of a "physical" invariant is ropelength, which is the length of unit-diameter rope needed to realize a particular knot type.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] In topology, **knot theory** is the study of mathematical knots.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] While inspired by knots which appear in daily life, such as those in shoelaces and rope, a mathematical knot differs in that the ends are joined so it cannot be undone, the simplest knot being a ring (or "unknot").
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] In mathematical language, a knot is an embedding of a circle in 3-dimensional Euclidean space, $\mathbb {E} ^{3}$ .
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Two mathematical knots are equivalent if one can be transformed into the other via a deformation of $\mathbb {R} ^{3}$ upon itself (known as an ambient isotopy); these transformations correspond to manipulations of a knotted string that do not involve cutting it or passing it through itself.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Using different description methods, there may be more than one description of the same knot.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] For example, a common method of describing a knot is a planar diagram called a knot diagram, in which any knot can be drawn in many different ways.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Therefore, a fundamental problem in knot theory is determining when two descriptions represent the same knot.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] A complete algorithmic solution to this problem exists, which has unknown complexity.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] In practice, knots are often distinguished using a *knot invariant*, a "quantity" which is the same when computed from different descriptions of a knot.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Important invariants include knot polynomials, knot groups, and hyperbolic invariants.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] The original motivation for the founders of knot theory was to create a table of knots and links, which are knots of several components entangled with each other.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] More than six billion knots and links have been tabulated since the beginnings of knot theory in the 19th century.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] To gain further insight, mathematicians have generalized the knot concept in several ways.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Knots can be considered in other three-dimensional spaces and objects other than circles can be used; see *knot (mathematics)*.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] For example, a higher-dimensional knot is an *n*-dimensional sphere embedded in (*n*+2)-dimensional Euclidean space.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Knot theory can also be extended to describe entanglement in open curves, which is used to study knots in proteins, DNA, and physical ropes.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Archaeologists have discovered that knot tying dates back to prehistoric times.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Besides their uses such as recording information and tying objects together, knots have interested humans for their aesthetics and spiritual symbolism.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Knots appear in various forms of Chinese artwork dating from several centuries BC (see Chinese knotting).
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] The endless knot appears in Tibetan Buddhism, while the Borromean rings have made repeated appearances in different cultures, often representing strength in unity.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] The Celtic monks who created the Book of Kells lavished entire pages with intricate Celtic knotwork.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] A mathematical theory of knots was first developed in 1771 by Alexandre-Théophile Vandermonde who explicitly noted the importance of topological features when discussing the properties of knots related to the geometry of position.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Mathematical studies of knots began in the 19th century with Carl Friedrich Gauss, who defined the linking integral (Silver 2006).
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] In the 1860s, Lord Kelvin's theory that atoms were knots in the aether led to Peter Guthrie Tait's creation of the first knot tables for complete classification.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Tait, in 1885, published a table of knots with up to ten crossings, and what came to be known as the Tait conjectures.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] This record motivated the early knot theorists, but knot theory eventually became part of the emerging subject of topology.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] These topologists in the early part of the 20th century—Max Dehn, J.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Alexander, and others—studied knots from the point of view of the knot group and invariants from homology theory such as the Alexander polynomial.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] This would be the main approach to knot theory until a series of breakthroughs transformed the subject.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] In the late 1970s, William Thurston introduced hyperbolic geometry into the study of knots with the hyperbolization theorem.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Many knots were shown to be hyperbolic knots, enabling the use of geometry in defining new, powerful knot invariants.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] The discovery of the Jones polynomial by Vaughan Jones in 1984 (Sossinsky 2002, pp.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] 71–89), and subsequent contributions from Edward Witten, Maxim Kontsevich, Louis Kauffman, and others, revealed deep connections between knot theory and mathematical methods in statistical mechanics and quantum field theory.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] A plethora of knot invariants have been invented since then, utilizing sophisticated tools such as quantum groups and Floer homology.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] In the last several decades of the 20th century, scientists became interested in studying physical knots in order to understand knotting phenomena in DNA and other polymers.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Knot theory can be used to determine if a molecule is chiral (has a "handedness") or not (Simon 1986).
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Tangles, strings with both ends fixed in place, have been effectively used in studying the action of topoisomerase on DNA (Flapan 2000).
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Knot theory may be crucial in the construction of quantum computers, through the model of topological quantum computation (Collins 2006).
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] On the left, the unknot, and a knot equivalent to it.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] It can be more difficult to determine whether complex knots, such as the one on the right, are equivalent to the unknot.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] A knot is created by beginning with a one-dimensional line segment, wrapping it around itself arbitrarily, and then fusing its two free ends together to form a closed loop (Adams 2004) (Sossinsky 2002).
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Simply, we can say a knot K is a "simple closed curve" (see Curve) — that is: a "nearly" injective and continuous function $K\colon [0,1]\to \mathbb {R} ^{3}$ , with the only "non-injectivity" being $K(0)=K(1)$ .
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Topologists consider knots and other entanglements such as links and braids to be equivalent if the knot can be pushed about smoothly, without intersecting itself, to coincide with another knot.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] The idea of **knot equivalence** is to give a precise definition of when two knots should be considered the same even when positioned quite differently in space.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] A formal mathematical definition is that two knots $K_{1},K_{2}$ are equivalent if there is an orientation-preserving homeomorphism $h\colon \mathbb {R} ^{3}\to \mathbb {R} ^{3}$ with $h(K_{1})=K_{2}$ .
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Conversely, two knots equivalent under the ambient isotopy definition are also equivalent under the orientation-preserving homeomorphism definition, because the $t=1$ (final) stage of the ambient isotopy must be an orientation-preserving homeomorphism carrying one knot to the other.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] One may try to define knot equivalence based on 'isotopy' instead of the more restricted property of ambient isotopy.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] That is, two knots are isotopic when there exists a continuous function starting at $t=0$ giving the $K_{1}$ embedding, ending at $t=1$ giving the $K_{2}$ embedding, with all intermediate values corresponding to embeddings.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] However, this definition would make every knot equivalent to the unknot, as the knotted portions can be "contracted" down to a straight line.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] The problem is that, while continuous, this is not an injective function of the euclidean space that the knot is embedded in.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Requiring that the homotopy be through homeomorphisms fixes this problem.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] The basic problem of knot theory, the **recognition problem**, is determining the equivalence of two knots.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Algorithms exist to solve this problem, with the first given by Wolfgang Haken in the late 1960s (Hass 1998).
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Nonetheless, these algorithms can be extremely time-consuming, and a major issue in the theory is to understand how hard this problem really is (Hass 1998).
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] The special case of recognizing the unknot, called the unknotting problem, is of particular interest (Hoste 2005).
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] In February 2021 Marc Lackenby announced a new unknot recognition algorithm that runs in quasi-polynomial time.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] A useful way to visualise and manipulate knots is to project the knot onto a plane—think of the knot casting a shadow on the wall.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] A small change in the direction of projection will ensure that it is one-to-one except at the double points, called *crossings*, where the "shadow" of the knot crosses itself once transversely (Rolfsen 1976).
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] At each crossing, to be able to recreate the original knot, the over-strand must be distinguished from the under-strand.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] This is often done by creating a break in the strand going underneath.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] The resulting diagram is an immersed plane curve with the additional data of which strand is over and which is under at each crossing.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] (These diagrams are called **knot diagrams** when they represent a knot and **link diagrams** when they represent a link.) Analogously, knotted surfaces in 4-space can be related to immersed surfaces in 3-space.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] A **reduced diagram** is a knot diagram in which there are no **reducible crossings** (also **nugatory** or **removable crossings**), or in which all of the reducible crossings have been removed.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] A petal projection is a type of projection in which, instead of forming double points, all strands of the knot meet at a single crossing point, connected to it by loops forming non-nested "petals".
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] In 1927, working with this diagrammatic form of knots, J.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Alexander and Garland Baird Briggs, and independently Kurt Reidemeister, demonstrated that two knot diagrams belonging to the same knot can be related by a sequence of three kinds of moves on the diagram, shown below.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Move one strand completely over another.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Move a strand completely over or under a crossing.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] The proof that diagrams of equivalent knots are connected by Reidemeister moves relies on an analysis of what happens under the planar projection of the movement taking one knot to another.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] The movement can be arranged so that almost all of the time the projection will be a knot diagram, except at finitely many times when an "event" or "catastrophe" occurs, such as when more than two strands cross at a point or multiple strands become tangent at a point.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] A close inspection will show that complicated events can be eliminated, leaving only the simplest events: (1) a "kink" forming or being straightened out; (2) two strands becoming tangent at a point and passing through; and (3) three strands crossing at a point.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] These are precisely the Reidemeister moves (Sossinsky 2002, ch.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] A knot invariant is a "quantity" that is the same for equivalent knots (Adams 2004) (Lickorish 1997) (Rolfsen 1976).
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] For example, if the invariant is computed from a knot diagram, it should give the same value for two knot diagrams representing equivalent knots.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] An invariant may take the same value on two different knots, so by itself may be incapable of distinguishing all knots.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] An elementary invariant is tricolorability.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] "Classical" knot invariants include the knot group, which is the fundamental group of the knot complement, and the Alexander polynomial, which can be computed from the Alexander invariant, a module constructed from the infinite cyclic cover of the knot complement (Lickorish 1997)(Rolfsen 1976).
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] In the late 20th century, invariants such as "quantum" knot polynomials, Vassiliev invariants and hyperbolic invariants were discovered.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] These aforementioned invariants are only the tip of the iceberg of modern knot theory.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] A knot polynomial is a knot invariant that is a polynomial.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Well-known examples include the Jones polynomial, the Alexander polynomial, and the Kauffman polynomial.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] A variant of the Alexander polynomial, the Alexander–Conway polynomial, is a polynomial in the variable *z* with integer coefficients (Lickorish 1997).
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] The Alexander–Conway polynomial is actually defined in terms of links, which consist of one or more knots entangled with each other.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] The concepts explained above for knots, e.g. diagrams and Reidemeister moves, also hold for links.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Consider an oriented link diagram, *i.e.* one in which every component of the link has a preferred direction indicated by an arrow.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] The original diagram might be either $L_{+}$ or $L_{-}$ , depending on the chosen crossing's configuration.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] The second rule is what is often referred to as a skein relation.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] To check that these rules give an invariant of an oriented link, one should determine that the polynomial does not change under the three Reidemeister moves.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Many important knot polynomials can be defined in this way.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] The following is an example of a typical computation using a skein relation.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] It computes the Alexander–Conway polynomial of the trefoil knot.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] The yellow patches indicate where the relation is applied.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] gives a link deformable to one with 0 crossings (it is actually the unlink of two components) and an unknot.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] which implies that *C*(unlink of two components) = 0, since the first two polynomials are of the unknot and thus equal.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Since the Alexander–Conway polynomial is a knot invariant, this shows that the trefoil is not equivalent to the unknot.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Actually, there are two trefoil knots, called the right and left-handed trefoils, which are mirror images of each other (take a diagram of the trefoil given above and change each crossing to the other way to get the mirror image).
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] These are not equivalent to each other, meaning that they are not amphichiral.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] This was shown by Max Dehn, before the invention of knot polynomials, using group theoretical methods (Dehn 1914).
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] But the Alexander–Conway polynomial of each kind of trefoil will be the same, as can be seen by going through the computation above with the mirror image.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] The *Jones* polynomial can in fact distinguish between the left- and right-handed trefoil knots (Lickorish 1997).
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] William Thurston proved many knots are hyperbolic knots, meaning that the knot complement (i.e., the set of points of 3-space not on the knot) admits a geometric structure, in particular that of hyperbolic geometry.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] The hyperbolic structure depends only on the knot so any quantity computed from the hyperbolic structure is then a knot invariant (Adams 2004).
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] are a link with the property that removing one ring unlinks the others.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] complement from the perspective of an inhabitant living near the red component.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Geometry lets us visualize what the inside of a knot or link complement looks like by imagining light rays as traveling along the geodesics of the geometry.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] An example is provided by the picture of the complement of the Borromean rings.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] The inhabitant of this link complement is viewing the space from near the red component.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] The balls in the picture are views of horoball neighborhoods of the link.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] By thickening the link in a standard way, the horoball neighborhoods of the link components are obtained.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Even though the boundary of a neighborhood is a torus, when viewed from inside the link complement, it looks like a sphere.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Each link component shows up as infinitely many spheres (of one color) as there are infinitely many light rays from the observer to the link component.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] The fundamental parallelogram (which is indicated in the picture), tiles both vertically and horizontally and shows how to extend the pattern of spheres infinitely.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] This pattern, the horoball pattern, is itself a useful invariant.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Other hyperbolic invariants include the shape of the fundamental parallelogram, length of shortest geodesic, and volume.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Modern knot and link tabulation efforts have utilized these invariants effectively.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Fast computers and clever methods of obtaining these invariants make calculating these invariants, in practice, a simple task (Adams, Hildebrand & Weeks 1991).
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] A knot in three dimensions can be untied when placed in four-dimensional space.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Suppose one strand is behind another as seen from a chosen point.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Lift it into the fourth dimension, so there is no obstacle (the front strand having no component there); then slide it forward, and drop it back, now in front.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Analogies for the plane would be lifting a string up off the surface, or removing a dot from inside a circle.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] In fact, in four dimensions, any non-intersecting closed loop of one-dimensional string is equivalent to an unknot.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] First "push" the loop into a three-dimensional subspace, which is always possible, though technical to explain.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Four-dimensional space occurs in classical knot theory, however, and an important topic is the study of slice knots and ribbon knots.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] A notorious open problem, often attributed to Ralph Fox, asks whether every slice knot is also ribbon.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] A knot is considered smoothly slice if it can be the boundary of a disk that is smoothly embedded in a four-dimensional ball.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] (The adjective "smoothly" is usually assumed, and smoothly slice knots are referred to as slice.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] There are other types of knots, such as rationally slice, which are not necessarily smoothly slice.) A ribbon knot is one that bounds a disk D immersed in the 3-sphere.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] All ribbon knots are known to be slice knots.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Since a knot can be considered topologically a 1-dimensional sphere, the next generalization is to consider a two-dimensional sphere ( $\mathbb {S} ^{2}$ ) embedded in 4-dimensional Euclidean space ( $\mathbb {R} ^{4}$ ).
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Such an embedding is knotted if there is no homeomorphism of $\mathbb {R} ^{4}$ onto itself taking the embedded 2-sphere to the standard "round" embedding of the 2-sphere.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Suspended knots and spun knots are two typical families of such 2-sphere knots.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] The mathematical technique called "general position" implies that for a given *n*-sphere in *m*-dimensional Euclidean space, if *m* is large enough (depending on *n*), the sphere should be unknotted.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] In general, piecewise-linear *n*-spheres form knots only in (*n* + 2)-dimensional space (Zeeman 1963), although this is no longer a requirement for smoothly knotted spheres.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] In fact, there are smoothly knotted $(4k-1)$ -spheres in 6*k*-dimensional space; e.g., there is a smoothly knotted 3-sphere in $\mathbb {R} ^{6}$ (Haefliger 1962) (Levine 1965).
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Thus the codimension of a smooth knot can be arbitrarily large when not fixing the dimension of the knotted sphere; however, any smooth *k*-sphere embedded in $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ with $2n-3k-3>0$ is unknotted.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] The notion of a knot has further generalisations in mathematics, see: Knot (mathematics), isotopy classification of embeddings.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Every knot in the *n*-sphere $\mathbb {S} ^{n}$ is the link of a real-algebraic set with isolated singularity in $\mathbb {R} ^{n+1}$ (Akbulut & King 1981).
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] An *n*-knot is a single $\mathbb {S} ^{n}$ embedded in $\mathbb {R} ^{m}$ .
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] An *n*-link consists of *k*-copies of $\mathbb {S} ^{n}$ embedded in $\mathbb {R} ^{m}$ , where *k* is a natural number.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Both the $m=n+2$ and the $m>n+2$ cases are well studied, and so is the $n>1$ case.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Two knots can be added by cutting both knots and joining the pairs of ends.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] The operation is called the *knot sum*, or sometimes the *connected sum* or *composition* of two knots.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] This can be formally defined as follows (Adams 2004): consider a planar projection of each knot and suppose these projections are disjoint.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Find a rectangle in the plane where one pair of opposite sides are arcs along each knot while the rest of the rectangle is disjoint from the knots.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Form a new knot by deleting the first pair of opposite sides and adjoining the other pair of opposite sides.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] The resulting knot is a sum of the original knots.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Depending on how this is done, two different knots (but no more) may result.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] This ambiguity in the sum can be eliminated regarding the knots as *oriented*, i.e. having a preferred direction of travel along the knot, and requiring the arcs of the knots in the sum are oriented consistently with the oriented boundary of the rectangle.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] The knot sum of oriented knots is commutative and associative.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] A knot is *prime* if it is non-trivial and cannot be written as the knot sum of two non-trivial knots.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] A knot that can be written as such a sum is *composite*.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] There is a prime decomposition for knots, analogous to prime and composite numbers (Schubert 1949).
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] For oriented knots, this decomposition is also unique.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Higher-dimensional knots can also be added but there are some differences.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] While you cannot form the unknot in three dimensions by adding two non-trivial knots, you can in higher dimensions, at least when one considers *smooth* knots in codimension at least 3.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Knots can also be constructed using the circuit topology approach.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] This is done by combining basic units called soft contacts using five operations (Parallel, Series, Cross, Concerted, and Sub).
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] The approach is applicable to open chains as well and can also be extended to include the so-called hard contacts.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] In a 2020 article (based on results originally obtained in the 1970s), V.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Nesterenok introduced a binary operation on the set of oriented knot isotopy classes ${\mathcal {K}}$ , denoted by $[\cdot ,\cdot ]:{\mathcal {K}}\times {\mathcal {K}}\to {\mathcal {K}}$ .
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] To define the operation for classes $\alpha$ and $\beta$ , representatives are chosen in the left and right half-spaces $\mathbb {R} _{-}^{3}$ and $\mathbb {R} _{+}^{3}$ respectively, such that their intersections with the separating plane are specific orthogonal segments.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] A pair of surfaces $V_{1}$ and $V_{2}$ cobounding these segments is constructed, and the operation $[\alpha ,\beta ]$ is defined as the isotopy class of the smoothed boundary of the union $\partial (V_{1}\cup V_{2})$ .
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] The operation is antisymmetric, satisfying $[\beta ,\alpha ]=-[\alpha ,\beta ]$ , and it has the standard trivial knot $\omega$ as a right null element: $[\alpha ,\omega ]=\omega$ .
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] A key topological property of this bracket operation is that it produces knots with a trivial Alexander–Conway polynomial; specifically, $\nabla ([\alpha ,\beta ])=1$ .
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] The article also establishes a relationship between this bracket operation and the HOMFLY-PT polynomial ${\mathcal {P}}$ , expressing ${\mathcal {P}}([\alpha ,\beta ])$ as a linear combination of the polynomials of the connected sums and the doubled components $D(\alpha )$ and $D(\beta )$ .
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Traditionally, knots have been catalogued in terms of crossing number.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Knot tables generally include only prime knots, and only one entry for a knot and its mirror image (even if they are different) (Hoste, Thistlethwaite & Weeks 1998).
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] The number of nontrivial knots of a given crossing number increases rapidly, making tabulation computationally difficult (Hoste 2005, p.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Tabulation efforts have succeeded in enumerating over 6 billion knots and links (Hoste 2005, p.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] While exponential upper and lower bounds for this sequence are known, it has not been proven that this sequence is strictly increasing (Adams 2004).
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] The first knot tables by Tait, Little, and Kirkman used knot diagrams, although Tait also used a precursor to the Dowker notation.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Different notations have been invented for knots which allow more efficient tabulation (Hoste 2005).
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] The early tables attempted to list all knots of at most 10 crossings, and all alternating knots of 11 crossings (Hoste, Thistlethwaite & Weeks 1998).
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] The development of knot theory due to Alexander, Reidemeister, Seifert, and others eased the task of verification and tables of knots up to and including 9 crossings were published by Alexander–Briggs and Reidemeister in the late 1920s.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] The first major verification of this work was done in the 1960s by John Horton Conway, who not only developed a new notation but also the Alexander–Conway polynomial (Conway 1970) (Doll & Hoste 1991).
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] This verified the list of knots of at most 11 crossings and a new list of links up to 10 crossings.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Conway found a number of omissions but only one duplication in the Tait–Little tables; however he missed the duplicates called the Perko pair, which would only be noticed in 1974 by Kenneth Perko (Perko 1974).
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] This famous error would propagate when Dale Rolfsen added a knot table in his influential text, based on Conway's work.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Conway's 1970 paper on knot theory also contains a typographical duplication on its non-alternating 11-crossing knots page and omits 4 examples — 2 previously listed in D.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] In the late 1990s Hoste, Thistlethwaite, and Weeks tabulated all the knots through 16 crossings (Hoste, Thistlethwaite & Weeks 1998).
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] In 2003 Rankin, Flint, and Schermann, tabulated the alternating knots through 22 crossings (Hoste 2005).
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] In 2020 Burton tabulated all prime knots with up to 19 crossings (Burton 2020).
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] This is the most traditional notation, due to the 1927 paper of James W.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Briggs and later extended by Dale Rolfsen in his knot table (see image above and List of prime knots).
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] The notation simply organizes knots by their crossing number.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] One writes the crossing number with a subscript to denote its order amongst all knots with that crossing number.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] This order is arbitrary and so has no special significance (though in each number of crossings the twist knot comes after the torus knot).
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Links are written by the crossing number with a superscript to denote the number of components and a subscript to denote its order within the links with the same number of components and crossings.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Thus the trefoil knot is notated 31 and the Hopf link is 22 1.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Alexander–Briggs names in the range 10162 to 10166 are ambiguous, due to the discovery of the Perko pair in Charles Newton Little's original and subsequent knot tables, and differences in approach to correcting this error in knot tables and other publications created after this point.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] The Dowker–Thistlethwaite notation, also called the Dowker notation or code, for a knot is a finite sequence of even integers.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] The numbers are generated by following the knot and marking the crossings with consecutive integers.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Since each crossing is visited twice, this creates a pairing of even integers with odd integers.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] An appropriate sign is given to indicate over and undercrossing.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] The Dowker–Thistlethwaite notation for this labelling is the sequence: 6, −12, 2, 8, −4, −10.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] A knot diagram has more than one possible Dowker notation, and there is a well-understood ambiguity when reconstructing a knot from a Dowker–Thistlethwaite notation.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] The Conway notation for knots and links, named after John Horton Conway, is based on the theory of tangles (Conway 1970).
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] The advantage of this notation is that it reflects some properties of the knot or link.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] The notation describes how to construct a particular link diagram of the link.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Start with a *basic polyhedron*, a 4-valent connected planar graph with no digon regions.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Such a polyhedron is denoted first by the number of vertices then a number of asterisks which determine the polyhedron's position on a list of basic polyhedra.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] For example, 10** denotes the second 10-vertex polyhedron on Conway's list.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Each vertex then has an algebraic tangle substituted into it (each vertex is oriented so there is no arbitrary choice in substitution).
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Each such tangle has a notation consisting of numbers and + or − signs.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] The 1* denotes the only 1-vertex basic polyhedron.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] The 2 −3 2 is a sequence describing the continued fraction associated to a rational tangle.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] One inserts this tangle at the vertex of the basic polyhedron 1*.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] A more complicated example is 8*3.1.2 0.1.1.1.1.1 Here again 8* refers to a basic polyhedron with 8 vertices.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] The periods separate the notation for each tangle.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Any link admits such a description, and it is clear this is a very compact notation even for very large crossing number.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] There are some further shorthands usually used.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] The last example is usually written 8*3:2 0, where the ones are omitted and kept the number of dots excepting the dots at the end.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] For an algebraic knot such as in the first example, 1* is often omitted.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Conway's pioneering paper on the subject lists up to 10-vertex basic polyhedra of which he uses to tabulate links, which have become standard for those links.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] For a further listing of higher vertex polyhedra, there are nonstandard choices available.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Gauss code, similar to the Dowker–Thistlethwaite notation, represents a knot with a sequence of integers.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] However, rather than every crossing being represented by two different numbers, crossings are labeled with only one number.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] When the crossing is an overcrossing, a positive number is listed.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Gauss code is limited in its ability to identify knots.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] This problem is partially addressed with by the extended Gauss code.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] While classical knot theory classifies embeddings via crossings, many naturally occurring folded chains include chain crossings along with intra-chain bonds not captured by traditional knot theoretic methods, and are primarily studied by Circuit topology.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] In 2019, Alireza Mashaghi and Colin Adams extended knot theory to 3D embeddings of linear chains with intra-chain bonds.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] They introduced generalized Reidemeister moves, adapted Gauss codes, and "bondles" (bonded quandles) as invariants to classify self-interacting open chains, revealing a richer knot hierarchy beyond classical invariants.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] Beyond pure mathematics, knot theory has found significant applications in a variety of scientific fields.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] In chemistry, it provides a framework for studying the chirality of molecules and for describing topologically non‑trivial structures such as catenanes and molecular knots, where the knottedness of the molecular backbone influences physical and chemical properties.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] In molecular biology, knot theory is used to analyze the action of enzymes like topoisomerases, which alter the linking number and supercoiling of DNA, and to model processes such as recombination and replication of circular DNA.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] In physics, knot invariants arise naturally in topological quantum field theory—for instance, the Jones polynomial emerges from Chern–Simons theory—and knot theoretic ideas are employed in the study of vortex dynamics, cosmic strings, and certain statistical mechanics models.
[src:knot-theory/knot-theory] More recently, methods from knot theory have been applied to quantum computing, where braid group representations serve as a model for topological qubits, and to materials science in the design of novel polymers and mechanical metamaterials.
[src:knot-theory/reidemeister-move] In the mathematical area of knot theory, a **Reidemeister move** is any of three local moves on a link diagram.
[src:knot-theory/reidemeister-move] Kurt Reidemeister (1927) and, independently, James Waddell Alexander and Garland Baird Briggs (1926), demonstrated that two knot diagrams belonging to the same knot, up to planar isotopy, can be related by a sequence of the three Reidemeister moves.
[src:knot-theory/reidemeister-move] Move a string completely over or under a crossing.
[src:knot-theory/reidemeister-move] No other part of the diagram is involved in the picture of a move, and a planar isotopy may distort the picture.
[src:knot-theory/reidemeister-move] The numbering for the types of moves corresponds to how many strands are involved, e.g. a type II move operates on two strands of the diagram.
[src:knot-theory/reidemeister-move] One important context in which the Reidemeister moves appear is in defining knot invariants.
[src:knot-theory/reidemeister-move] By demonstrating a property of a knot diagram which is not changed when we apply any of the Reidemeister moves, an invariant is defined.
[src:knot-theory/reidemeister-move] Many important invariants can be defined in this way, including the Jones polynomial.
[src:knot-theory/reidemeister-move] The type I move is the only move that affects the writhe of the diagram.
[src:knot-theory/reidemeister-move] The type III move is the only one which does not change the crossing number of the diagram.
[src:knot-theory/reidemeister-move] In applications such as the Kirby calculus, in which the desired equivalence class of knot diagrams is not a knot but a framed link, one must replace the type I move with a "modified type I" (type I') move composed of two type I moves of opposite sense.
[src:knot-theory/reidemeister-move] The type I' move affects neither the framing of the link nor the writhe of the overall knot diagram.
[src:knot-theory/reidemeister-move] Trace (1983) showed that two knot diagrams for the same knot are related by using only type II and III moves if and only if they have the same writhe and winding number.
[src:knot-theory/reidemeister-move] Furthermore, combined work of Östlund (2001), Manturov (2004), and Hagge (2006) shows that for every knot type there are a pair of knot diagrams so that every sequence of Reidemeister moves taking one to the other must use all three types of moves.
[src:knot-theory/reidemeister-move] Alexander Coward demonstrated that for link diagrams representing equivalent links, there is a sequence of moves ordered by type: first type I moves, then type II moves, type III, and then type II.
[src:knot-theory/reidemeister-move] The moves before the type III moves increase crossing number while those after decrease crossing number.
[src:knot-theory/reidemeister-move] Hayashi (2005) proved there is also an upper bound, depending on crossing number, on the number of Reidemeister moves required to split a link.
[src:knot-theory/reidemeister-move] Coward & Lackenby (2014) proved the existence of an exponential tower upper bound (depending on crossing number) on the number of Reidemeister moves required to pass between two diagrams of the same link.
[src:knot-theory/reidemeister-move] In detail, let n be the sum of the crossing numbers of the two diagrams, then the upper bound is $2^{2^{2^{.^{.^{n}}}}}$ where the height of the tower of 2 s (with a single n at the top) is $10^{1,000,000n}$ .
[src:knot-theory/reidemeister-move] Lackenby (2015) proved the existence of a polynomial upper bound (depending on crossing number) on the number of Reidemeister moves required to change a diagram of the unknot to the standard unknot.
[src:knot-theory/reidemeister-move] In detail, for any such diagram with c crossings, the upper bound is $(236c)^{11}$ .
